Linux
Open source operating system
Components: Shell and kernel
Kernel: core of OS, interacts with hardware. Manages system, user input/output, processes, files, memory and devices.
Shell is used to interact with kernel. User input.

File system:
Files represented with "-" in cmd line.
Directory is special type of file. Holds info about other files. "d" in CLI.

/Root partition. Only root user has write privileges here. /root is not same as /./root which is home directory of root.
/bin contains binary executables. ls, cat, so on...
/sbin system maintenance executables. iptables, ifconfig, reboot.
/etc  config files of programs.
/var variable files, logs, changing files
/tmp temp files
/home users dir, personal files.
/boot boot loader files.


Run levels: 
0 Halt shuts down all services and system not rebooted
1 Single user, used for maintenance, no network capabilities.
2 Multi user, for maintenance and sys testing
3 Multiuser Non GUI mode for server systems
4 custom mode used by SysAdmins
5 Graphical GUI login with run level 3
6 Reboot - shuts down all services when sys is being rebooted


Basic commands:

cd - change directory
cp - copies files or dirs
mv - moves files or directories
ls - list information
df - display sys disk space
kill - kill process
rm - delete file or dir
rmdir - deletes empty dir.
cat - display content of file or combine files.
mkdir - create dirs
ifconfig - ip information, network configuration
locate - quick search of files, updated by updatedb
tail - view end of text file, 10 lines
less - view large files part
more - display text, on screen at a  time
nano - basic text editor.
cmdnod - changes privilefes for file or dir.


Permisions and owners:
Three groups: user, group, everybody
read 4 (100), write 2 (010), execute 1(001)

Change permissions:
chmod <permision> filename
Chomod u=rw, g=r,o=r <filename>
chown changes owner adn group owner of a file 


